Task 2: Student Digital Portfolio

GitHub is a platform where developers store and manage their code, and it uses Git to keep track of all the changes made over
time. 
I created a profile README, which acts like a short introduction page. 
In it, I included my basic details suchas my branch, current year, and what I aim to learn. Even though it may seem simple, 
it is important because it is the first thing anyone notices when they visit a GitHub profile.

LinkedIn is a professional networking platform used by recruiters and companies, so creating an account felt necessary.
I added my educational details, including VIT Bhopal, my course in Computer Science Engineering, and my expected graduation
year.
Since I am still in my early years, I don’t have much experience to add yet, but setting up the profile is a good starting 
point.

Kaggle is a platform by Google that focuses on data science and machine learning. I signed up for it because of my AI/ML 
course this semester. It seemed like a natural place to begin. 
Although I haven’t explored it much yet, I plan to use it in the future.

I had never really thought about this before—that building a professional online presence isn’t something you start just 
before placements, but something you begin working on from the very first year.

Over the next four years, I plan to use GitHub for every project I work on, LinkedIn to fill out as I have things happen, 
and Kaggle once I get into the AI/ML course. 
Overall, this task helped me understand that building a professional presence should start early and grow over time.
